 {"id":"coding_agent_session_search-3iafm","title":"Enable BEGIN CONCURRENT for parallel indexer writes","description":"TRACK: cass storage migration (Track 3B)
PARENT EPIC: Complete frankensqlite Integration

WHAT: Leverage frankensqlite's MVCC concurrent writers (BEGIN CONCURRENT) to eliminate the single-writer bottleneck in the indexer.

VERIFIED FRANKENSQLITE CONCURRENT SUPPORT:
- BEGIN CONCURRENT is FULLY IMPLEMENTED
- SSI (Serializable Snapshot Isolation) handles conflict detection at page level
- Error types: BusySnapshot (retry needed), WriteConflict, SerializationFailure
- Connection has: last_local_commit_seq(), current_concurrent_snapshot_seq() for observability
- VfsOpenFlags supports necessary access modes

CURRENT CASS ARCHITECTURE (src/indexer/mod.rs):
- spawn_connector_producer(): spawns per-connector threads that scan and parse sessions
- Single consumer thread receives NormalizedConversation via crossbeam channel
- Consumer calls storage.insert_conversations_batched() which holds a write lock
- LazyDb: parking_lot::Mutex<Option<Connection>> — single connection, single writer

DEEP AUDIT FINDINGS (critical implementation details):

1. insert_conversations_batched() takes `&mut self` on SqliteStorage:
   - Signature: pub fn insert_conversations_batched(&mut self, conversations: &[(i64, Option<i64>, &Conversation)]) -> Result<Vec<InsertOutcome>>
   - This means each thread needs its OWN FrankenStorage instance (not shared)
   - Connection factory must return new FrankenStorage per producer thread
   - Alternative: refactor insert_conversations_batched to take &Connection directly

2. Memory scaling concern:
   - Current PRAGMAs set mmap_size=256MB per connection
   - 15 producer connections x 256MB = 3.84GB mmap overhead
   - DECISION NEEDED: reduce per-connection mmap_size for writer connections (they don't need read perf), or use frankensqlite's native memory model which may not use mmap at all

3. FTS5 batch optimization must be preserved:
   - Current code disables FTS triggers before batch insert, rebuilds after
   - With concurrent writers, FTS rebuild coordination is needed
   - Options: (a) each writer rebuilds its own FTS entries, (b) single post-batch FTS rebuild, (c) frankensqlite FTS5 may handle this differently
   - Must verify frankensqlite FTS5 concurrent write behavior

4. Tantivy index coordination:
   - Indexer also builds tantivy full-text index alongside SQLite
   - Tantivy IndexWriter is NOT thread-safe for concurrent add_document()
   - Options: (a) keep tantivy writes serialized via channel/mutex, (b) use per-thread IndexWriter (not recommended), (c) migrate tantivy to frankensearch-lexical management
   - RECOMMENDATION: Keep tantivy writes on a single thread (the existing consumer pattern) even if SQLite writes go parallel. The tantivy bottleneck is much smaller than the SQLite bottleneck.

NEW ARCHITECTURE WITH CONCURRENT WRITERS:
1. connection_factory(db_path, pragmas) -> FrankenStorage  
   - Returns a new FrankenStorage with PRAGMAs applied
   - Writer connections get reduced mmap_size (or none if frankensqlite doesn't use mmap)
2. Each connector producer thread: let storage = factory() -> storage.insert_conversations_batched() inside BEGIN CONCURRENT
3. Tantivy indexing stays serialized: producers send indexed-tantivy-docs via crossbeam channel to a single tantivy writer thread
4. frankensqlite SSI handles SQLite conflict detection (page-level conflicts)
5. Different connectors write different conversations -> conflicts should be extremely rare

RETRY LOGIC:
```rust
loop {
    conn.execute("BEGIN CONCURRENT")?;
    match do_inserts(&conn) {
        Ok(()) => { conn.execute("COMMIT")?; break; }
        Err(FrankenError::BusySnapshot | FrankenError::WriteConflict) => {
            conn.execute("ROLLBACK")?;
            std::thread::sleep(backoff.next());
        }
        Err(e) => return Err(e),
    }
}
```

PERFORMANCE IMPACT:
- 15 connectors scanning independently -> SQLite writes could speed up 3-10x
- Eliminates the crossbeam channel + single-consumer serialization bottleneck for SQLite
- Tantivy writes remain serialized (acceptable — tantivy indexing is fast)
- Readers (search, TUI) are NEVER blocked by writers (MVCC snapshot isolation)

RISK: frankensqlite is relatively new — concurrent writing at scale needs thorough stress testing (see stress test bead). Validate with realistic cass workloads before making default.

FILES TO MODIFY: src/indexer/mod.rs (parallel write architecture), src/storage/sqlite.rs (connection factory)","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-02-27T05:25:38.684219Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-02T08:12:23.889480Z","closed_at":"2026-03-02T08:12:23.889454Z","close_reason":"done","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"coding_agent_session_search-3iafm","depends_on_id":"coding_agent_session_search-2agcj","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-02-27T05:28:00.119733Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}],"comments":[{"id":501,"issue_id":"coding_agent_session_search-3iafm","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"BEGIN CONCURRENT implementation completed and tested. Changes:

